  "prompt": "Can you get the flu even after vaccination?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to get the flu even after receiving the flu vaccine, though the vaccine significantly reduces the risk. Here\u2019s why:\n\n1. **Vaccine Effectiveness**: The flu vaccine is designed to protect against the most common and likely flu strains predicted for each season. However, its effectiveness varies from year to year (typically 40\u201360%) because the circulating flu strains can change or differ from the strains included in the vaccine.\n\n2. **Immune Response**: Individual immune systems vary. Some people may not develop a strong enough immune response after vaccination to fully protect against the virus.\n\n3. **Timing of Vaccination**: It takes about two weeks after vaccination for the body to build immunity. If you\u2019re exposed to the flu virus shortly before or after getting the vaccine, you might still get sick.\n\n4. **Mismatched Strains**: If the vaccine does not closely match the circulating flu strains, it may be less effective.\n\n5. **Other Respiratory Illnesses**: Some illnesses (e.g., the common cold, COVID-19) have flu-like symptoms, which can be mistaken for the flu.\n\nEven if you do get the flu after vaccination, the symptoms are often milder and the risk of severe complications, hospitalization, or death is significantly reduced. This is why health experts still strongly recommend getting the flu vaccine every year.",
